(82, 0, 'The LOST GUGE KINGDOM (US$.2900)', 'The-LOST-GUGE-KINGDOM', 'package-main-photo-61b896ee494fc.jpg', '<p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;mso-ascii-theme-font:\r\nminor-latin;mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">What\r\nis Tibet Travel Permit &amp; How can I obtain the permit?</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">Tibet Travel\r\nPermit is a must for Tibet tour. Its cost is included in the tour quotation.\r\nSend your passport and China visa copies to us&nbsp;<strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin;\r\nmso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">20 days</span></strong>&nbsp;in\r\nadvance, and we will apply for the permit after you book a Tibetan tour with\r\nus. Shortly after we get your permit from Tibet Tourism Bureau, we will inform\r\nyou and mail it to your hotel in China via express.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">In some extreme\r\ncases, our staff will hand it over to you at the airport or railway station. In\r\nour experience, we can virtually guarantee to get your permit during times when\r\nTibet is open to foreign travelers.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;mso-ascii-theme-font:\r\nminor-latin;mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">What\r\ntype of Accommodation on the tour?</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">Tibet is never\r\nknown for its 5-star luxury resorts, though you can find some like\r\nIntercontinental Lhasa Paradise, St.Regis Lhasa Resort, Sheraton hotel, etc in\r\nLhasa. Overall, the accommodation facilities and services are not as good as\r\nthose in coastal and central parts of China. However, from cheap and clean\r\nyouth hotel, to distinct Tibetan style 3-star and international 5-star luxury\r\nhotel, you will find one that suits your interest and pocket in Lhasa.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">We’ve handpicked\r\ncozy and safe hotels in the central area of Lhasa, where you will find Jokhang\r\nTemple and Barkhor Street are just steps away from you. You can easily\r\nexperience more of the local life and culture. Normally, as you travel to\r\nremote areas in some parts of Shigatse like Tingri, or EBC, Ngari, Nagqu, etc.\r\nthe accommodation would be much poorer. Some may have air-conditioning in the\r\nhotel;others may only have electric blanket in the guesthouses. And the food is\r\nalso very basic.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;mso-ascii-theme-font:\r\nminor-latin;mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">How\r\nto Tip Guide &amp; Staff</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">Our\r\nEnglish-speaking guides are natives of Tibet with good knowledge of Tibetan\r\nculture, history, and Buddhism. Most are trained to offer Western-standard\r\nservice. Throughout your stay in Tibet, we will minor your health and provide\r\nprompt help to you. If you run into any trouble, please do not hesitate to\r\nreach them or our customer service manager.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">Travelers’s\r\ntipping to Tibetan guide and driver is taken as an extra gratitude to their\r\ngood service, just like what you do in the west. Normally, a tipping of&nbsp;<strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin;\r\nmso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">7 USD/day</span></strong>&nbsp;is\r\nacceptable. The basic rule is good service for good pay.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;mso-ascii-theme-font:\r\nminor-latin;mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">How\r\nare the Toilet’s on the remote region?</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:\r\n10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">Admittedly, to\r\nmany western tourists, using toilets in Tibet is the most dreadful experience.\r\nSo, please down play your expectation. If you take Tibet train to Lhasa, both\r\nwestern toilet and squat toilet are available in the train. If you stay in\r\nhotel above 3-star hotels in Lhasa, Shigatse, etc. you will have no complaining\r\nusing standard western flash toilet.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">However, if you\r\nvisit some of the attractions like Yamdrok or Namtso, EBC outdoor, mostly you\r\nwill see the smelly and filthy pit toilet.It\'s better to carry enough toilet\r\npaper.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;mso-ascii-theme-font:\r\nminor-latin;mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">What\r\nkind of weather to expect in Tibet?</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">One of the\r\nbiggest features of weather on Qinghai-Tibet Plateau is the dramatic\r\ntemperature change between day and night. The annual temperature in Lhasa is -2</span><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Cambria Math&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;mso-bidi-font-family:\r\nCalibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">℃</span><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">-- 12</span><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Cambria Math&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;mso-bidi-font-family:\r\nCalibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">℃</span><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">(spring), 9</span><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Cambria Math&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;mso-bidi-font-family:\r\nCalibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">℃</span><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">-- 22</span><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Cambria Math&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;mso-bidi-font-family:\r\nCalibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">℃</span><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">(summer), 7</span><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Cambria Math&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;mso-bidi-font-family:\r\nCalibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">℃</span><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">-- 19</span><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Cambria Math&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;mso-bidi-font-family:\r\nCalibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">℃</span><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">(fall), -7</span><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Cambria Math&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;mso-bidi-font-family:\r\nCalibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">℃</span><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">-- 9</span><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Cambria Math&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;mso-bidi-font-family:\r\nCalibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">℃</span><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">(winter). Do wear\r\nclothes properly such as thermal tops, fleece jacket, breathable underwear,\r\ndown jacket, jeans, beanie, etc.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">Of course, sun\r\nscreen, lip balm, sun glasses are essential to shield you from powerful\r\nblinding sunlight on the plateau. Do drink more water and eat more vegetable as\r\nyou travel in Tibet. It can prevent you from dehydration.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;mso-ascii-theme-font:\r\nminor-latin;mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">How\r\nto acclimatize to the High Altitude?</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:\r\n10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">For the first timer\r\nto Tibet, either by flight or train, a good rest is a must for quick\r\nacclimation to the high altitude in Lhasa. Never rush to tour the street or\r\nattractions on your own. Walk slower and do not exert yourself like running or\r\njumping. Spending at least two days in Lhasa is a good way to get acclimatized\r\nbefore heading to Shigatse or Namtso. If you have any discomfort, do tell it to\r\nyour guide,and he will help you out.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;mso-ascii-theme-font:\r\nminor-latin;mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">Any\r\nOther Dos and Don\'ts?</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:\r\nCalibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">Normally, taking\r\nphotos is forbidden in the monastery. If you want to take photos of Tibetan\r\npilgrims, a gentle ask of permission would be appreciated or you can do it from\r\na long distance. Swimming and fishing are not allowed in holy lakes in Tibet;\r\nDo not talk about sensitive topics like politics; International tourists are\r\nnot allowed to travel alone in Tibet according to the policy; Walk clockwise\r\naround Barkhor Street; Never venture into the unknown trails; do as much as you\r\ncan to protect the fragile eco-system in Tibet, etc.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\" style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin\">As Tibetan\r\nBuddhism is deeply-rooted in every facet of Tibetans\' life, always follow and\r\nrespect the unique customs in Tibet. If you are uncertain about something, it’s\r\nadvisable to ask your guide before you do it at will.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>', 'The LOST KINGDOM “GUGE with Mt. Kailash via Toling & Tsaparang on far South West of Tibetan world highest plateau is absolutely a perfect combination of program just out of the world. Mt. Kailash with Guge Kingdom, once a forbidden kingdom in the early 10th and 11th century where famous old Silk Road passed by this route towards India-Pakistan- China and Nepal at present where you can visit to see its ancient remains of ruined forts and houses with much history that lies hidden in this old Empire of Toling-Tsparang and Lost Guge Kingdom.', '29.6472,91.1174', '2 Pax', 'APR MAY OCT', 'Adventurous', '02nd April 2022', '2022/04/02', '2022/04/21', '2022/03/01', NULL, '<p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 01:&nbsp;Arrive\r\nKathmandu meet assistance and drive to Hotel.</p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day\r\n02:&nbsp;Kathmandu sightseeing of Boudha Stupa, Swoyambhu &amp; Durbar Square.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 03:&nbsp;Drive\r\nKtm to Syabrubesi 1,460 m via Trisuli Bazaar and Dhunche 1,950 m - 07 hrs.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 04:&nbsp;Drive\r\nto&nbsp;Kyirong 3,950 m&nbsp;(Kyirong - Dzonka County) camp or in local\r\nguesthouse.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 05:&nbsp;In\r\nKyirong rest day for acclimatization.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 06:&nbsp;Drive\r\nto Saga 4,400m - 05 hrs.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 07:&nbsp;Drive\r\nto Paryang 4,550 m - 06 hrs.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 08:&nbsp;Drive\r\nto Manasarover 4,550 m - 06 hrs<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 09:&nbsp;Rest\r\nday for acclimatization in Lake Manasarovar.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 10:&nbsp;Drive\r\nto Tarboche near Darchen 4,600m walk to Dhiraphuk 4,900 m.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 11:&nbsp;Trek\r\nto Zutul-Puk 4,760 m via Dorma-la 5, 470 m.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 12:&nbsp;Trek\r\nnear Darchen drive to Tirthapuri 4,840 m - 04 hrs.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 13:&nbsp;Drive\r\nto Toling 4,700 m - 05 hrs.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 14:&nbsp;At\r\nToling with day trip to Tsaparang and eventually drive downhill to LOST GUGE Kingdom.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 15:&nbsp;Morning\r\nExplore LOST KINGDOM and later drive to Darchen - 06 hrs.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 16:&nbsp;Drive\r\nto Saga - 07 hrs.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 17:&nbsp;Drive\r\nto Kyirong Border<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 18:&nbsp;Drive\r\nto Dhunche town 1,950 m - 06 hrs.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 19:&nbsp;Drive\r\nback to Kathmandu and transfer to hotel - 06 hrs.<o:p></o:p></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNoSpacing\">Day 20:&nbsp;Drive\r\nto international airport for onwards departure back home..<o:p></o:p></p>', 2900, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;mso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;\r\ncolor:#595959;border:none windowtext 1.0pt;mso-border-alt:none windowtext 0in;\r\npadding:0in\">Privacy policy</span><span style=\"font-size:13.5pt;font-family:\r\n&quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;mso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;color:#29293A\"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"font-size:9.0pt;font-family:\r\n&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;mso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;color:#595959;\r\nborder:none windowtext 1.0pt;mso-border-alt:none windowtext 0in;padding:0in\">Any\r\npersonal information that we collect about you may be used for any purpose\r\nassociated with the operation of a Trip or to send you marketing material in\r\nrelation to our events and special offers. We will otherwise treat your details\r\nin accordance with our privacy policy (available for viewing on our Website).</span><span style=\"font-size:5.0pt;font-family:&quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;mso-fareast-font-family:\r\n&quot;Times New Roman&quot;\"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;T